Date: Thu, 23 Jul 2026 02:33:20 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 1/2] futex: Retain FUTEX_WAITERS across a contended robust
 unlock

The FUTEX_ROBUST_UNLOCK operation releases the futex word by storing
zero and then wakes the requested number of waiters. Storing zero wipes
the FUTEX_WAITERS bit even when more waiters remain queued on the futex,
which makes the wakeup chain depend on the survival of the woken waiter:

 1) T1 owns the futex, T2 and T3 are blocked in futex_wait(). The futex
    word is 'T1 | FUTEX_WAITERS'.

 2) T1 unlocks with FUTEX_WAKE | FUTEX_ROBUST_UNLOCK. The kernel stores
    zero and wakes T2. T3 remains queued.

 3) T4 acquires the futex through the uncontended fast path. The futex
    word is 'T4', FUTEX_WAITERS is lost.

 4) T2 is killed before it can retry the futex and re-instate the
    FUTEX_WAITERS bit.

 5) The robust list exit processing of T2 finds a pending op pointing at
    a futex owned by T4. It cannot distinguish this situation from an
    unrelated lock attempt, so it rightfully does nothing.

 6) T4 unlocks. The futex word is 'T4', i.e. uncontended, so the unlock
    takes the __vdso_futex_robust_list*_try_unlock() fast path and wakes
    nobody.

T3 is blocked forever.

Instead of trying to recover from this situation in the robust list exit
processing after the fact, prevent it: store FUTEX_WAITERS instead of
zero when waiters remain queued after the wakeup. The contention
information then lives in the futex word rather than in the woken task:
the acquisition in step 3) has to take the contended path - a cmpxchg
which preserves FUTEX_WAITERS - and the unlock in step 6) fails the vDSO
fast path and wakes T3.

If the woken waiter is killed while the futex word is still released
(owner portion zero), the existing pending op handling in
handle_futex_death() wakes the next waiter, whether FUTEX_WAITERS is set
or not.

The remaining waiter check and the store must be serialized against
futex_wait() enqueueing new waiters, i.e. performed inside the hash
bucket lock section: a waiter either revalidates the futex word under
the hash bucket lock after the store - observing the released value and
returning -EAGAIN - or is enqueued before the check and thus accounted
for in the stored value. The current implementation stores before taking
the hash bucket lock; with such an unsynchronized store a waiter can
block on the pre-release value after the remaining waiter check without
being counted, and is stranded the same way.

Therefore restructure the robust unlock into a dedicated function which
counts the queued waiters, performs the store and collects the wakeups
in one hash bucket lock section. The unconditional pre-lock store and
the hash bucket waiters fast path are dropped for the robust unlock: the
uncontended case is handled in the vDSO helper, so a robust unlock
syscall is contended by definition.

This changes the FUTEX_ROBUST_UNLOCK ABI contract, which has not been in
a released kernel yet: user space must treat a futex word with a zero
TID portion as free regardless of FUTEX_WAITERS, acquire it with a
cmpxchg which preserves the bit, and never wait on such a word. A
pthread_mutex_lock() style lock loop needs most of this behavior anyway
to take over a released word, but the glibc slow path currently treats
any nonzero futex word as owned and would block on FUTEX_WAITERS, so
this must land before user space adopts the new ABI.

Both the revised protocol and the requirement for the in-lock store were
validated with a TLA+ model of the lock/unlock/exit protocol: TLC finds
the lost wakeup above with the store-zero semantics as well as with an
unsynchronized store, and verifies that with retained FUTEX_WAITERS
every queued waiter is eventually woken across arbitrary task deaths.

Fixes: 3ca9595d9fb6 ("futex: Add support for unlocking robust futexes")
Signed-off-by: Keno Fischer <keno@juliahub.com>
Assisted-by: ClaudeCode:claude-fable-5 tla+
---
 Documentation/locking/robust-futex-ABI.rst |  17 +++-
 include/vdso/futex.h                       |   3 +-
 kernel/futex/waitwake.c                    | 113 +++++++++++++++++++--
 3 files changed, 120 insertions(+), 13 deletions(-)

diff --git a/Documentation/locking/robust-futex-ABI.rst b/Documentation/locking/robust-futex-ABI.rst
index 5e6a0665b8ba..7e83b3d6f4f0 100644
--- a/Documentation/locking/robust-futex-ABI.rst
+++ b/Documentation/locking/robust-futex-ABI.rst
@@ -215,8 +215,21 @@ For the contended unlock case, where other threads are waiting for the lock
 release, there's the ``FUTEX_ROBUST_UNLOCK`` operation feature flag for the
 ``futex()`` system call, which must be used with one of the following
 operations: ``FUTEX_WAKE``, ``FUTEX_WAKE_BITSET`` or ``FUTEX_UNLOCK_PI``.
-The kernel will release the lock (set the futex word to zero), clean the
-``list_op_pending`` field. Then, it will proceed with the normal wake path.
+The kernel will release the lock, clean the ``list_op_pending`` field and
+wake the requested number of waiters. The value stored into the futex word
+by the release reflects the remaining contention: if waiters remain queued
+in the kernel after the wakeup, the futex word is set to ``FUTEX_WAITERS``,
+otherwise to zero. This keeps subsequent lock acquisitions on the contended
+path so that every unlock wakes the next waiter, even if a woken waiter is
+killed before it can take over the lock in user space (the released,
+ownerless futex word also lets the robust list exit handling of such a
+waiter wake its successor).
+
+Lock implementations using ``FUTEX_ROBUST_UNLOCK`` must therefore treat a
+futex word whose TID portion is zero as free regardless of the
+``FUTEX_WAITERS`` bit: it is acquired with an atomic compare-and-exchange
+which preserves ``FUTEX_WAITERS``, and a thread must never wait on a futex
+word with a zero TID portion.
 
 For the non-contended path, there's still a race between checking the futex word
 and clearing the ``list_op_pending`` field. To solve this without the need of a
diff --git a/include/vdso/futex.h b/include/vdso/futex.h
index 3cd175eefe64..2c5caaf9fbfe 100644
--- a/include/vdso/futex.h
+++ b/include/vdso/futex.h
@@ -32,7 +32,8 @@
  *
  * If the unlock attempt fails due to the FUTEX_WAITERS bit set in the lock,
  * then the syscall does the unlock, clears the pending op pointer and wakes the
- * requested number of waiters.
+ * requested number of waiters. The unlock leaves FUTEX_WAITERS set in the
+ * futex word when further waiters remain queued after the wakeup.
  */
 __u32 __vdso_futex_robust_list64_try_unlock(__u32 *lock, __u32 tid, __u64 *pop);
 
diff --git a/kernel/futex/waitwake.c b/kernel/futex/waitwake.c
index d4483d15d30a..aa407284bf52 100644
--- a/kernel/futex/waitwake.c
+++ b/kernel/futex/waitwake.c
@@ -150,26 +150,118 @@ void futex_wake_mark(struct wake_q_head *wake_q, struct futex_q *q)
 }
 
 /*
- * If requested, clear the robust list pending op and unlock the futex
+ * FUTEX_ROBUST_UNLOCK: release the futex word, clear the robust list
+ * pending op and wake up to @nr_wake waiters.
+ *
+ * The value stored into the futex word depends on whether waiters remain
+ * queued after the wakeup: if so, the word is set to FUTEX_WAITERS instead
+ * of 0. A woken waiter can be killed before it acquires the lock in user
+ * space. If the futex word was simply zeroed, a third task could take the
+ * lock through the uncontended fast path in that window and its subsequent
+ * unlock would not wake anybody, leaving the remaining waiters blocked
+ * forever. The robust list exit handling cannot recover from that either:
+ * the futex word contains the new owner's TID, which does not match the
+ * dying waiter's.
+ *
+ * Keeping FUTEX_WAITERS set forces such acquisitions onto the contended
+ * path: the released word is not 0, so taking the lock requires a cmpxchg
+ * which preserves FUTEX_WAITERS, and the subsequent unlock takes the
+ * syscall path and wakes the next waiter. If the woken waiter is killed
+ * before acquiring the lock, the exit handling covers it instead:
+ * handle_futex_death() wakes a waiter for a pending op whose futex word
+ * has an all zero owner portion, whether FUTEX_WAITERS is set or not.
+ *
+ * The store must be performed inside the hash bucket lock section so that
+ * it is serialized against futex_wait() enqueueing further waiters: a
+ * waiter either revalidates the futex word after the store - observing the
+ * released value and returning -EAGAIN - or is enqueued before the
+ * remaining waiter check and thus represented in the stored value. With
+ * the store performed before taking the hash bucket lock, a waiter could
+ * block on the pre-release value after the check without being counted,
+ * and be stranded the same way.
  */
-static bool futex_robust_unlock(u32 __user *uaddr, unsigned int flags, void __user *pop)
+static int futex_robust_unlock_wake(u32 __user *uaddr, unsigned int flags,
+				    void __user *pop, int nr_wake, u32 bitset,
+				    union futex_key *key)
 {
-	if (!(flags & FLAGS_ROBUST_UNLOCK))
-		return true;
+	bool wake = !((flags & FLAGS_STRICT) && !nr_wake);
+	int ret = 0, nqueued, nwake;
+	struct futex_q *this, *next;
+	DEFINE_WAKE_Q(wake_q);
+	bool scan_done;
+	u32 mval;
 
-	/* First unlock the futex, which requires release semantics. */
+	CLASS(hbr, hbr)(key);
+	auto hb = hbr.hb;
+
+retry:
+	spin_lock(&hb->lock);
+
+	/*
+	 * Count the queued waiters and how many of them the wakeup below
+	 * will wake, replicating its iteration: waiters which do not match
+	 * @bitset are skipped, a PI waiter terminates the walk.
+	 */
+	nqueued = nwake = 0;
+	scan_done = false;
+	plist_for_each_entry(this, &hb->chain, list) {
+		if (!futex_match(&this->key, key))
+			continue;
+		nqueued++;
+		if (scan_done || !wake)
+			continue;
+		if (this->pi_state || this->rt_waiter)
+			scan_done = true;
+		else if ((this->bitset & bitset) && ++nwake >= nr_wake)
+			scan_done = true;
+	}
+
+	mval = nqueued > nwake ? FUTEX_WAITERS : 0;
+
+	/* Unlock the futex, which requires release semantics. */
+	pagefault_disable();
 	scoped_user_write_access(uaddr, efault)
-		unsafe_atomic_store_release_user(0, uaddr, efault);
+		unsafe_atomic_store_release_user(mval, uaddr, efault);
+	pagefault_enable();
+
+	if (wake) {
+		plist_for_each_entry_safe(this, next, &hb->chain, list) {
+			if (futex_match(&this->key, key)) {
+				if (this->pi_state || this->rt_waiter) {
+					ret = -EINVAL;
+					break;
+				}
+
+				/* Check if one of the bits is set in both bitsets */
+				if (!(this->bitset & bitset))
+					continue;
+
+				this->wake(&wake_q, this);
+				if (++ret >= nr_wake)
+					break;
+			}
+		}
+	}
+
+	spin_unlock(&hb->lock);
 
 	/*
 	 * Clear the pending list op now. If that fails, then the task is in
 	 * deeper trouble as the robust list head is usually part of the TLS.
 	 * The chance of survival is close to zero.
 	 */
-	return futex_robust_list_clear_pending(pop, flags);
+	if (!futex_robust_list_clear_pending(pop, flags))
+		ret = -EFAULT;
+
+	wake_up_q(&wake_q);
+	return ret;
 
 efault:
-	return false;
+	pagefault_enable();
+	spin_unlock(&hb->lock);
+	if (fault_in_user_writeable(uaddr))
+		return -EFAULT;
+	goto retry;
 }
 
 /*
@@ -189,8 +281,9 @@ int futex_wake(u32 __user *uaddr, unsigned int flags, void __user *pop, int nr_w
 	if (unlikely(ret != 0))
 		return ret;
 
-	if (!futex_robust_unlock(uaddr, flags, pop))
-		return -EFAULT;
+	if (flags & FLAGS_ROBUST_UNLOCK)
+		return futex_robust_unlock_wake(uaddr, flags, pop, nr_wake,
+						bitset, &key);
 
 	if ((flags & FLAGS_STRICT) && !nr_wake)
 		return 0;
-- 
